Saul of corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my place, drunk.
So I suggested he not drive.
He asked me why.
"You have drunk," I said to him, "are you not afraid of the police?"
Boris replied to me: "No, I have a document with Benjamin Franklin's effigy, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with a $100 bill slipped next to it.
Obviously, I knew that the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris would meet a policeman who was not corrupt.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to enter the police force assigned to traffic, you have to buy your chief's silence.
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your chief's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things the right way drown in bureaucratic hassles.
By paying 100 dollars, you can drive around town without brakes!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels seen today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom none are offered, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or an abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officials and even the Kremlin: no one anywhere is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious and tastelessly decorated houses, I asked who owned them and heard in response that one belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of Moscow's prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax office employee.
Corruption now represents for Russia a more serious threat than the Chechen war.
Indeed, the Chechen war would not have lasted so long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought 120 kilograms of explosives used in the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims died during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from smelling them.
A precaution quite useless.
No one controls the buses today.
The driver, who did not know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same thing.
A policeman would come to him and ask: "do you know what the price is?", and the driver would reply: "of course, I know", paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, or even days for the entire journey.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because the Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaïda and all the "international terrorist" network, but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves, who first tax the Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to the terrorists, maps indicating where the minefields are, and provide the rebels with false documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers who fight the rebels have, on the contrary, stocks of ammunition, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more harshly?
That would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more you will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those called « the simple people » view this phenomenon with kindness.
They say of their mayor « of course he steals, but look at all he has done for the city! »
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the conductor both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor had stopped her, telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on board the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will erase your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, sickened by the corruption of Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since, the situation has worsened.
Removing corruption could well leave the State without citizens, but if the progression of corruption is not stopped, the citizens will soon be left without a State.
